| RIAA Secretly Tries to Get ISP Subscriber Info                     |
|   from the always-with-the-plotting-and-planning-are-they dept.    |
|   posted by Zonk on Friday April 27, @11:53 (Privacy)              |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/27/1439245          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]NewYorkCountryLawyer writes "In an attempt to change the rules of the
game, [1]the RIAA secretly went to a federal district court in Denver
with an ex parte application. The goal was to get the judge to rule that
the federal Cable Communications Policy Act [2]does not apply to the
RIAA's attempts to get subscriber information (pdf) from cable companies.
Just to clarify, ex parte means that the application was secret, no one
else — neither the ISP nor the subscribers — were given notice that this
was going on. They were, in effect, asking the Court to rule that the
RIAA does not need to get a court order to be able to force an ISP to
disclose confidential subscriber information. The Magistrate Judge
[3]declined to rule on the issue (pdf), but did give them the ex parte
discovery order they were looking for."

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/27/1439245

Links:
    0. http://recordingindustryvspeople.blogspot.com/
    1. http://recordingindustryvspeople.blogspot.com/2007/04/riaa-goes-into-court-ex-parte-in-denver.html
    2. http://www.ilrweb.com/viewILRPDF.asp?filename=arista_does1-9_memooflaw
    3. http://www.ilrweb.com/pfdocuments/ilrpdfs/arista_v_does_1-9.pdf


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Ohio Audit Reveals More Diebold Problems                           |
|   from the must-offer-witty-comment-on-unsurprising-situation dept.|
|   posted by Zonk on Friday April 27, @12:33 (Security)             |
|   http://politics.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/27/1515255     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

armb writes with a link to a Wired Blog entry about [0]irregularities
found in Diebold databases from the state of Ohio. The election in
question here is November 2006, and the corruption of the entries may
raise doubts about accurate tabulations. "Vote totals in two separate
databases that should have been identical had different totals. Although
Diebold explained that this was part of the system design for separate
vote tables to get updated at different times during the tabulation
process, the team questioned the wisdom of a design that creates
non-identical vote totals. Tables in the database contained elements that
were missing date and time stamps that would indicate when information
was entered. Entries that did have date/time stamps showed a January 1,
1970 date. The database is built from Microsoft's Jet database engine.
The engine, according to Microsoft, is vulnerable to corruption when a
lot of concurrent activity is happening with the database, such as what
occurs on an election night when results are uploaded and various servers
are interacting with the database simultaneously."

Discuss this story at:
    http://politics.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/27/1515255

Links:
    0. http://blog.wired.com/27bstroke6/2007/04/diebold_vote_da.html


