|   from the next-step-is-fuchikomas dept.                           |
|   posted by Zonk on Friday April 27, @16:32 (Science)              |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/27/203208       |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

SpeedyTrain writes with a link to a story on the Mainichi Daily News site
about [0]the future of mass transit in Japan. Despite problems with
Maglev technology in test-bed scenarios around the world, Japan has
committed to building a line between Tokyo and Nagoya by 2025. The
experimental system will allow trains to run at up to 310 miles an hour.
"The new magnetically levitated, or "maglev," trains would slash the
100-minute travel time down the country's busiest transportation corridor
and are envisioned as a successor for Japan's iconic bullet trains, or
shinkansen, first introduced to the world in 1964 ... [a] spokeswoman
declined to give an estimate for the cost of linking the capital with the
Nagoya area about 269 kilometers (168 miles) to the west. But Kyodo News
agency said the whole project would cost about 9 trillion yen (US$76.3
billion) and be divided between the company and the central and local
governments."

