| Jobs Says People Don't Want to 'Rent' Music                        |
|   from the money-can-be-exchanged-for-good-and-services dept.      |
|   posted by Zonk on Friday April 27, @17:52 (Music)                |
|   http://apple.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/27/2011206        |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]eldavojohn writes "PhysOrg is running a piece on [1]a recent speech by
Apple CEO Steve Jobs about DRM free music. While we know that Jobs is a
[2]self proclaimed proponent of DRM free music who's [3]not all talk,
he's now said that 'by the end of this year, over half of the songs we
offer on iTunes we believe will be in DRM-free versions. I think we're
going to achieve that.' Jobs pointed out what's obvious to us, the
consumers, but isn't obvious to the music industry — 'People want to own
their music.' He also dismissed subscription based music as a failure,
and claimed a lot of other music labels are intrigued by the EMI deal."

